This year was arguably one of the most challenging years of my life.. beyond spending a majority of the year recovering from a major surgery the mental game was even harder. I felt every emotion all at once and at the same time — nothing at all. A vast and deep emptiness that I’ve never experienced before. I lost myself and almost thought I would never come back. I wasn’t physically able to paint for months and when I finally picked up a brush I convinced myself I had lost my spark. I cried (a lot) and layed in the dark and eventually picked up the pieces and made myself whole again. I learned that the most important thing in life is your people & I have many to thank beyond the ones in this post (hopefully u know who u are 🫶🏽). I’m also thanking ✨me✨ for getting myself through this — every days still a challenge but I feel stronger and closer to my sense of self than ever before. Here’s to a new year 🤍

I’ve been asked quite a bit recently if I’m accepting commissions! The short answer is yes, but the long answer is — it depends. 

For the first 2 solid years of my career, I relied heavily on commissions within my classic marbled style of work. You all supported me and gave me the ability to quit my job and pursue art full time. I’ll forever be grateful 💌

Since then, I’ve reflected much more on what my art means to me, what I’m trying to communicate and express rather than just what looks pretty (although obviiii still gonna be makin pretty things til the day I die 🌟) I’ve also had to find new ways to paint and create - the painting method in this vid + my back injury is a major no no lolll. I’ve been in a big phase of experimentation and with that, it’s been hard and scary to let go of what originally tethered me and was a lot easier to generate income from.

This piece, VIRTUE, is likely the last piece I will create from my older style & she is ~available~ for purchase on my site. She’s an ode to my early days and a super special piece - hung above my bed until she finds her perfect home with a collector 🤍I’m excited to work together on new commissions that align our vision and my dms are open!

Ive been a full time artist for nearly 2 years now, and here’s some of my best advice! 
—
1. Social media is your best friend & is a huge reason I was able to pursue art full time. Short form video is KING rn - document your process! 

2. Delegate!! I’m such a control freak but once you can afford to, hire out the tedious tasks. Running a business is 10 million different components and you’ll constantly feel scattered & overwhelmed trying to conquer them all yourself. 

3. Create a mini community of art friends :) this career can be lonely but having a community to bounce ideas off, ask questions, collab and connect with is amazing. Some of my best friends are from the internet! 

4. Stay true to yourself. Once your passion becomes your source of income, it’s easy to get lost in chasing the next paycheck or making things that will sell. Authenticity will get you further in the long run. 

5. Last & most FAVORITE - DND🌙 My phones been on do not disturb for literally 2 years lol. I check it when I need to but when your work phones also your business phone, constant buzzing can kill your focus. Give yourself some peace!! 

If you have more questions ask in the comments!! 
#artist #fulltimeartist #artadvice #creativecareer #creativecommunity

I started experimenting with machine learning at the end of 2022 after my spinal injury when I was bored and stuck in bed. Although I had a lot of mixed feelings about AI in general, I think what piqued my interest the most was utilizing machine learning like a conversation back and forth between computer and human, between physical and digital realm. 

I trained numerous models, starting with a data set of the complete collection of my paintings from 2017 on, and as I was ebbing and flowing through different styles and mediums, the generations were just as chaotic and unrecognizable. I ended up creating new digital work, inputs of colors & gradients that excited me, and pulling textures and patterns from my old soaked film archives to refine the model to something that felt more in tune with the physical work I was creating.

These generations have become a blend of all mediums of my past, and have manifested into some of my favorite projects, the latest being these acrylic prints that I showed at my last LA show.  Sadly, the print shop absolutely butchered the job with printing errors and broken bits (that’s a whole other story) so I hadn’t really felt like sharing but hoping to get these done properly soon - a fun mix & match configurable offering to customize in your space. Excited to continue these digital conversations and see how they transform in the coming years!

Some looks into the process:
1/2: 12x12” Acrylic prints with chrome polished brass hardware
3: Early generations
4: Early generation sequence, almost there but still quite chaotic. My print ‘Anhedonia’ was pulled from this and painted over.
5: Sequence I created from the newer model - I wanted to convey the experience of going through an array of emotions in a matter of seconds (would love to add a score to this)
6. Coasters Season_006
7. Collaboration with @opi creating a nail set inspired by the work 
8. Mockup for the LA show w/ @projekt.______
